1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,360
So recently I stumbled upon this wonderful article in Tin House's Writer's Notebook 2.

2
00:00:04,460 --> 00:00:08,000
It was basically a schematic or a blueprint for how to put a short story together,

3
00:00:08,100 --> 00:00:10,940
even if you've never written one before, and it was kind of genius.

4
00:00:11,220 --> 00:00:14,320
The author was Antonio Nelson, who has published seven short story collections

5
00:00:14,320 --> 00:00:18,500
and also published in this very tiny little magazine you've probably never heard of, The New Yorker.

6
00:00:18,560 --> 00:00:23,040
So I figured, hey, this is somebody who I should really listen to about how to construct a short story.

7
00:00:23,140 --> 00:00:27,260
I started my career writing short stories, I published a collection of short stories with Press 53,

8
00:00:27,260 --> 00:00:30,780
and I won some big short story contests too, like Shenandoah and Third Coast,

9
00:00:30,880 --> 00:00:33,040
and I got one published in the Chicago Tribune as well.

10
00:00:33,120 --> 00:00:37,600
So I decided to test her short story method out, and I wrote it over a single day,

11
00:00:37,720 --> 00:00:39,600
and it actually worked quite well.

12
00:00:39,700 --> 00:00:42,540
And I even like it a week later, which is actually quite unusual.

13
00:00:42,740 --> 00:00:46,060
Normally I'm like in my editor mode, and I'm like, kill, kill, delete, delete.

14
00:00:46,220 --> 00:00:49,400
But no, I read it again, and I'm like, all right, this is actually good.

15
00:00:49,520 --> 00:00:52,740
Now I tend not to like overly prescriptive advice when it comes to fiction writing,

16
00:00:52,740 --> 00:00:57,160
but I found that these nine steps gave you plenty of leeway and creativity

17
00:00:57,160 --> 00:01:01,880
while simultaneously giving enough framework to guide you in the writing of a short story.

18
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:02,940
So here are the nine steps.

19
00:01:03,060 --> 00:01:06,480
And along the way, I'm going to give lots of examples from famous short stories,

20
00:01:06,540 --> 00:01:09,980
and also explain how I wrote my short story using this advice.

21
00:01:10,240 --> 00:01:12,640
One, write a story about something that's happened to you.

22
00:01:12,720 --> 00:01:16,980
I think she starts with this because tapping into a story that you know from your own life

23
00:01:16,980 --> 00:01:21,980
is a really good way to get to material with deeper weight that has real significance.

24
00:01:21,980 --> 00:01:26,860
If you struggle with infertility, or you've gone through a divorce, or you suffered from a theft,

25
00:01:26,860 --> 00:01:30,320
all of these things are elements that you can turn into a story.

26
00:01:30,540 --> 00:01:34,340
And don't feel constrained by what actually happened in real life.

27
00:01:34,620 --> 00:01:37,580
What happened in real life is just the starting point for your story.

28
00:01:37,660 --> 00:01:40,140
Perhaps in real life, you had an illness which made you sick,

29
00:01:40,240 --> 00:01:43,760
but in your story, you want to up the stakes a little bit, maybe make it life-threatening.

30
00:01:43,880 --> 00:01:47,700
Perhaps you were in love with someone in real life, but to spice it up in the story,

31
00:01:47,820 --> 00:01:51,800
you add another person who was vying for your beloved's attention.

32
00:01:51,960 --> 00:01:53,340
And so now it's sort of this love triangle.

33
00:01:53,440 --> 00:01:56,700
And when you look at short stories, there's actually quite a lot of famous short stories

34
00:01:56,700 --> 00:01:59,020
that just draw from the author's experience.

35
00:01:59,260 --> 00:02:02,680
James Baldwin's Sunny Blues draws from his experience growing up in Harlem.

36
00:02:02,840 --> 00:02:07,740
Philip Ross' Goodbye Columbus draws from his experiences of growing up as a Jew in New Jersey.

37
00:02:07,860 --> 00:02:11,760
Tim O'Brien's The Things They Carry draws from his experience of fighting in the Vietnam War.

38
00:02:11,860 --> 00:02:14,320
And because Alice Munro just died, bless her heart,

39
00:02:14,380 --> 00:02:16,680
I have to bring up her short story, Boys and Girls,

40
00:02:16,780 --> 00:02:19,320
which mirrored her own upbringing in Canada.

41
00:02:19,320 --> 00:02:23,440
For my short story, I'm a big chess player, so I wrote about going to a chess tournament.

42
00:02:23,560 --> 00:02:26,640
And I did so thinking, hey, Queen's Gambit was amazing.

43
00:02:26,860 --> 00:02:29,000
Everybody seemed to love and watch that show,

44
00:02:29,080 --> 00:02:32,040
so I felt like there was a market there for this type of story.

45
00:02:32,160 --> 00:02:35,760
Nelson's second step, write the same story from a different point of view.

46
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:37,260
Nelson, you're a genius.

47
00:02:37,500 --> 00:02:41,740
This is an essential step because it's teaching you how to rotate between

48
00:02:41,740 --> 00:02:45,840
a whole bunch of different perspectives to try to find the exact right perspective

49
00:02:45,840 --> 00:02:47,220
to tell the story from.

50
00:02:47,220 --> 00:02:52,080
After all, the best way to tell the story might not feature you as the main character.

51
00:02:52,240 --> 00:02:56,480
Sometimes authors write pretty decent stories that would be amazing stories

52
00:02:56,700 --> 00:02:58,200
if they were just told from a different point of view.

53
00:02:58,200 --> 00:03:01,020
The neighbor's point of view, or the spouse's point of view,

54
00:03:01,020 --> 00:03:05,020
the child's point of view, or even, say, the gun's point of view.

55
00:03:05,020 --> 00:03:08,300
Yes, you can write a story from an inanimate POV.

56
00:03:08,340 --> 00:03:10,260
Although don't try that tricky stuff too often.

57
00:03:10,300 --> 00:03:13,580
Now, this is a great step because I don't think you can truly understand your story

58
00:03:13,580 --> 00:03:15,980
until you've looked at it from multiple points of view.

59
00:03:16,020 --> 00:03:18,320
Now, how do you choose between all these different points of view?

60
00:03:18,360 --> 00:03:23,300
Ideally, you want to choose one from a perspective of someone who has something at stake in the story.

61
00:03:23,340 --> 00:03:25,560
What's going to happen if they don't get what they want?

62
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:27,160
A wife might have her marriage at stake.

63
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:29,080
A husband might have his career at stake.

64
00:03:29,160 --> 00:03:32,440
A neighbor might have his very happiness at stake.

65
00:03:32,440 --> 00:03:34,480
And maybe he's considering suicide or something.

66
00:03:34,640 --> 00:03:36,180
And as you're playing with these points of view,

67
00:03:36,280 --> 00:03:39,180
don't forget that you might end up with a very weird point of view.

68
00:03:39,440 --> 00:03:42,540
Like Jorge Luis Borges, he has a short story called The House of Asterion,

69
00:03:42,620 --> 00:03:45,180
where he writes it from the perspective of a minotaur.

70
00:03:45,320 --> 00:03:49,000
Yeah, that minotaur, like the Greek myth type of minotaur.

71
00:03:49,120 --> 00:03:53,140
So don't be afraid of considering lots of options for what point of view you can tell the story from.

72
00:03:53,240 --> 00:03:55,260
Now, for my story, I didn't make up my point of view.

73
00:03:55,260 --> 00:03:57,120
I chose a character who was female.

74
00:03:57,260 --> 00:04:00,160
So I had a strong feminine lead as the narrator.

75
00:04:00,420 --> 00:04:03,780
Nelson's third step out of the nine is to create a ticking clock.

76
00:04:03,900 --> 00:04:06,600
A ticking clock is a countdown to a particular event.

77
00:04:06,680 --> 00:04:10,060
Think about how many high school stories have a countdown to prom at the end of the year.

78
00:04:10,160 --> 00:04:14,680
Or think about how every single road trip is structured so we're looking forward to the end.

79
00:04:14,780 --> 00:04:18,520
For any sort of summer romance, it's confined within the summer.

80
00:04:18,620 --> 00:04:21,620
So we know there's an end point at the end of the summer when the story is going to end.

81
00:04:21,720 --> 00:04:23,760
Ooh, I said end way too many times there.

82
00:04:23,760 --> 00:04:24,640
End, end, end.

83
00:04:24,840 --> 00:04:25,080
End.

84
00:04:25,260 --> 00:04:25,860
End, end.

85
00:04:25,940 --> 00:04:28,920
So a ticking clock pressurizes your book.

86
00:04:29,020 --> 00:04:31,420
It gives the reader something to look forward to.

87
00:04:31,520 --> 00:04:34,620
They are counting down until they reach that climactic event.

88
00:04:34,720 --> 00:04:37,740
It creates tension in the story and it creates suspense in the story

89
00:04:37,740 --> 00:04:39,720
because the reader wants to know how it's going to end.

90
00:04:39,800 --> 00:04:42,940
Kind of like how in this video, you're looking forward to the ninth step of this guide.

91
00:04:43,040 --> 00:04:45,460
I've structured this video so it's ticking towards the finale.

92
00:04:46,080 --> 00:04:47,520
Think of the ticking clock of Cinderella.

93
00:04:47,760 --> 00:04:51,220
We have that midnight hour and she's going to transform back.

94
00:04:51,220 --> 00:04:54,300
And so we're anticipating that as readers to see what will happen.

95
00:04:54,420 --> 00:04:55,240
Or a movie like Run.

96
00:04:55,260 --> 00:05:00,240
Lola Run, where she has 20 minutes to find 100,000 Deutschmarks in order to save her boyfriend.

97
00:05:00,420 --> 00:05:01,720
Or the recent show would be The Bear.

98
00:05:01,860 --> 00:05:05,640
And this cooking show has a ticking clock in a lot of the episodes.

99
00:05:05,840 --> 00:05:08,160
It's always super high stakes and super high pressure.

100
00:05:08,320 --> 00:05:09,040
And they have a deadline.

101
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:12,340
One example from that show is Carmi's renovation of his restaurant.

102
00:05:12,440 --> 00:05:13,060
Super expensive.

103
00:05:13,060 --> 00:05:17,740
And he has 18 months to pay back Uncle Jimmy or else he's going to bulldoze the whole thing.

104
00:05:17,840 --> 00:05:21,420
Now, for my story, the ticking clock was the countdown to the chess tournament, right?

105
00:05:21,420 --> 00:05:23,820
At the beginning of the story, I announced the chess tournament.

106
00:05:23,960 --> 00:05:25,040
And it's working towards.

107
00:05:25,260 --> 00:05:26,800
That climactic event.

108
00:05:26,800 --> 00:05:28,560
So we're waiting until it happens.

109
00:05:28,620 --> 00:05:31,140
The fourth step is to create props or objects.

110
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:34,660
From Frodo's ring to that spinning top in Inception.

111
00:05:34,740 --> 00:05:37,680
Objects are never merely objects in fiction.

112
00:05:37,720 --> 00:05:40,460
They're always endowed with this potency.

113
00:05:40,500 --> 00:05:41,280
They're totems.

114
00:05:41,280 --> 00:05:43,680
They have this outsized power and meaning.

115
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:46,280
So the next step is to pick an object for your story.

116
00:05:46,320 --> 00:05:47,840
This could be a bracelet.

117
00:05:47,920 --> 00:05:49,260
It could be a stamp.

118
00:05:49,320 --> 00:05:51,140
It could be a poker set.

119
00:05:51,220 --> 00:05:53,920
Now, here's some advice on how to choose a good object.

120
00:05:53,960 --> 00:05:54,180
One.

121
00:05:54,180 --> 00:05:55,260
It's always good to have some sort of.

122
00:05:55,300 --> 00:05:57,420
Sentimental attachment to that object.

123
00:05:57,460 --> 00:05:57,800
Two.

124
00:05:57,840 --> 00:06:01,260
Look for a way for that object to be involved in the plot in some way.

125
00:06:01,300 --> 00:06:03,380
What does it make one of the characters do?

126
00:06:03,420 --> 00:06:05,440
How does it change them throughout the story?

127
00:06:05,480 --> 00:06:07,580
You want to make sure it's necessary for the story.

128
00:06:07,620 --> 00:06:09,700
And if you took it out of the story, the story wouldn't work.

129
00:06:09,760 --> 00:06:10,280
And three.

130
00:06:10,320 --> 00:06:17,180
I would recommend trying to choose not a typical object, but a slightly rare or more unusual object.

131
00:06:17,220 --> 00:06:22,340
An engagement ring might be a powerful object, but it might be also too cliche of an object.

132
00:06:22,380 --> 00:06:25,100
Now, you don't want this object to appear only once.

133
00:06:25,100 --> 00:06:27,140
It might be a symbol for a story.

134
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:32,020
You want to make sure you have a piece of the story that's inside the story and then just vanish during the second half.

135
00:06:32,060 --> 00:06:35,220
Ideally, you'll have this object throughout all different points in the story.

136
00:06:35,260 --> 00:06:37,320
Say, the beginning, the middle, and the end.

137
00:06:37,360 --> 00:06:41,820
Now, if the entire story really does revolve around this object, then it's called a MacGuffin.

138
00:06:41,860 --> 00:06:46,240
Think of the Philosopher's Stone in Harry Potter or the Heart of the Ocean necklace in Titanic.

139
00:06:46,280 --> 00:06:49,900
But you don't have to have the entire story revolve around that central object.

140
00:06:49,940 --> 00:06:54,240
It might just be sort of a symbolic object for one of the characters.

141
00:06:54,300 --> 00:06:55,000
For an example of this.

142
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:55,340
The movie.

143
00:06:55,380 --> 00:06:58,340
There were two shirts, one denim, one plaid that hung in the closet.

144
00:06:58,380 --> 00:07:00,180
Those shirts really aren't a plot device.

145
00:07:00,220 --> 00:07:02,800
They are more of a symbol of those cowboys love.

146
00:07:02,840 --> 00:07:06,760
Now, for my story, I thought a chess piece was too cliche of an object, too obvious.

147
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:13,380
So instead, it was her father's championship football ring, which was all that she had left of him after he had died.

148
00:07:13,420 --> 00:07:16,680
So to her, it symbolized the mindset of a champion.

149
00:07:16,720 --> 00:07:19,100
Five, create a transitional situation.

150
00:07:19,140 --> 00:07:23,300
This is probably the trickiest step out of all nine of them to understand and to implement.

151
00:07:23,340 --> 00:07:24,900
So a transitional moment.

152
00:07:24,900 --> 00:07:31,820
Is just some sort of crux in your character's lives when they are moving from one mode of existence to the next step of their existence.

153
00:07:31,860 --> 00:07:33,400
It could be a job change.

154
00:07:33,440 --> 00:07:36,160
It could be an actual move from one side of the country to the other.

155
00:07:36,200 --> 00:07:40,920
It could be a move out of marriage or into one in a good man is hard to find by Flannery O'Connor.

156
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:44,840
It's when they take a road trip and end up getting lost in the secret life of Walter Mitty.

157
00:07:44,880 --> 00:07:54,880
It's when Walter stops dreaming about taking adventures and actually goes on one in Minority Report, Tom Cruise's transition is when he stops being the lead of the pre-crime unit and starts.

158
00:07:54,900 --> 00:07:57,300
Being the suspect of a crime that hasn't been committed.

159
00:07:57,340 --> 00:08:08,480
Now, if you're trying to find your transitional moment, a good technique to do it is to say the phrase and then one day and figure out what happens that changes from the status quo to the new part of your character's existence.

160
00:08:08,520 --> 00:08:09,980
That is your transitional moment.

161
00:08:10,020 --> 00:08:16,920
And then one day now I have to say this in many short stories that transitional moment might be very small.

162
00:08:16,960 --> 00:08:18,100
It might be very delicate.

163
00:08:18,140 --> 00:08:19,940
It doesn't have to be life altering.

164
00:08:19,980 --> 00:08:24,320
That's because so many writers have been trained in movies and novels.

165
00:08:24,360 --> 00:08:24,880
So they're looking.

166
00:08:24,920 --> 00:08:26,560
For these giant shifts.

167
00:08:26,600 --> 00:08:29,400
But short stories are more delicate, subtle things.

168
00:08:29,440 --> 00:08:31,920
You might need a very small transitional moment.

169
00:08:31,960 --> 00:08:35,400
It might be a very internal transition for your character.

170
00:08:35,440 --> 00:08:37,200
It might be some kind of epiphany.

171
00:08:37,240 --> 00:08:41,440
In my story, it was my character deciding to participate in a chess tournament for the very first time.

172
00:08:41,480 --> 00:08:42,720
She was out of her comfort zone.

173
00:08:42,760 --> 00:08:45,960
She didn't know what was going to happen, but she decided to try.

174
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:50,040
The sixth step is to add a world event for the reader.

175
00:08:50,080 --> 00:08:53,280
You want to connect the world to the story in some way.

176
00:08:53,320 --> 00:08:54,640
Imagine being a reader.

177
00:08:54,640 --> 00:08:57,920
And stepping into a short story where they have no reference points.

178
00:08:57,960 --> 00:08:59,320
They don't know what's going on.

179
00:08:59,360 --> 00:09:00,960
Perhaps they don't even know you as an author.

180
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:08,880
It makes it much easier to trust you as an author if they can step in and immediately see a famous figure they know or a historical event that they're familiar with.

181
00:09:08,920 --> 00:09:14,840
For example, if a story takes place at a Thanksgiving dinner, the reader automatically has a connection to that story.

182
00:09:14,880 --> 00:09:16,840
They've been like, oh, I've been to a Thanksgiving dinner.

183
00:09:16,880 --> 00:09:18,120
They have emotions about it.

184
00:09:18,160 --> 00:09:20,080
And so that's their way into the story.

185
00:09:20,120 --> 00:09:24,520
And what's even better is when it comes time to market the short story or market the short story collection.

186
00:09:24,520 --> 00:09:30,160
You will have a touch point that you can use for marketing because it's something that readers can latch onto really quickly.

187
00:09:30,200 --> 00:09:37,560
For example, the short story collection by Hilary Mantel, The Assassination of Margaret Thatcher, gave a way for readers to immediately connect with that story collection.

188
00:09:37,600 --> 00:09:40,600
It's also an element of veracity, right?

189
00:09:40,640 --> 00:09:47,480
The reader feels like this story is true because there are real world events and real world people that are inhabiting it.

190
00:09:47,520 --> 00:09:51,880
It's just one more thing that convinces the reader what they're reading feels true.

191
00:09:51,920 --> 00:09:54,400
Now, I don't mean merely to name drop a famous story.

192
00:09:54,400 --> 00:09:56,400
I don't mean to say that a story is a famous person.

193
00:09:56,440 --> 00:09:58,440
I don't think that was what Nelson was going for.

194
00:09:58,480 --> 00:10:00,480
It has to be pretty central to the story in some way.

195
00:10:00,520 --> 00:10:09,520
For my story, there was cheating at the chess tournament, which I feel like tapped into a trending moment because there's been lots of stories of chess cheaters in the last year or two.

196
00:10:09,560 --> 00:10:15,560
And yes, news stories or current world events or something is always a great thing to include in your story.

197
00:10:15,600 --> 00:10:17,600
The seventh step is to add binary forces.

198
00:10:17,640 --> 00:10:23,680
This is just basically a fancy way to say create opposition or opposites inside your short story.

199
00:10:23,680 --> 00:10:26,760
The way I like to do this is to make characters who are opposites.

200
00:10:26,800 --> 00:10:29,440
It's not the only way, but it's the way I would start with.

201
00:10:29,480 --> 00:10:34,840
Consider an uneducated person against an uneducated person, like in Good Country People by Flannery O'Connor.

202
00:10:34,880 --> 00:10:39,440
In that story, you have a one legged PhD who gets duped by an uneducated Bible salesman.

203
00:10:39,480 --> 00:10:42,200
Or consider innocent versus experienced.

204
00:10:42,240 --> 00:10:44,440
In Joyce Carol Oates, Where Are You Going, Where Have You Been?

205
00:10:44,480 --> 00:10:48,840
You have this very youthful, very inexperienced 15 year old Connie.

206
00:10:48,880 --> 00:10:53,680
And against her in opposition, you have this very experienced, predatory 30 year old man.

207
00:10:53,720 --> 00:10:54,480
Arnold Friend.

208
00:10:54,520 --> 00:10:57,280
You could have oppositions like closed mind versus open minded.

209
00:10:57,320 --> 00:11:05,800
In Cathedral by Raymond Carver, you have one character who is very bigoted and very closed minded and who resents the blind friend of his wife who is coming to town.

210
00:11:05,840 --> 00:11:08,280
But the blind man who comes to town is very open minded.

211
00:11:08,320 --> 00:11:09,400
He's very insightful.

212
00:11:09,440 --> 00:11:10,440
He's very confident.

213
00:11:10,480 --> 00:11:11,920
A complete contrast.

214
00:11:11,960 --> 00:11:14,360
Or you could set up oppositions like winner versus loser.

215
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:21,360
I don't know if you remember reading this in high school, but the most dangerous game about a man hunting another man on an island for sport.

216
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:22,360
It's a classic.

217
00:11:22,400 --> 00:11:23,560
But there we have the opposition.

218
00:11:23,680 --> 00:11:25,400
The opposition of hunter versus prey.

219
00:11:25,440 --> 00:11:29,360
And we want to keep reading to see whether those roles will be reversed at any point.

220
00:11:29,400 --> 00:11:36,600
So when you have binary forces in your story and when you're creating opposites, you are creating tension because those characters are going to butt heads.

221
00:11:36,640 --> 00:11:42,040
And the more opposed your characters are, the more chances you have to put them into sharp conflict with each other.

222
00:11:42,080 --> 00:11:53,200
That means your job as a writer is to stretch them further apart from each other, to exaggerate their differences, because that space will allow you lots of narrative room to play and have fun and

223
00:11:53,200 --> 00:11:54,640
create a little messy conflict.

224
00:11:54,680 --> 00:11:55,840
All right, we're almost finished here.

225
00:11:55,880 --> 00:11:56,640
Two more steps.

226
00:11:56,680 --> 00:11:58,480
The eighth step is Freitag's Pyramid.

227
00:11:58,520 --> 00:12:02,640
So a lot of Nelson's advice so far has been focusing on certain portions of the story.

228
00:12:02,680 --> 00:12:06,320
Now we're going to look at the story as a whole and think, how do we shape this story?

229
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:08,560
What happens sequentially in a plot?

230
00:12:08,600 --> 00:12:13,000
And so Freitag's Pyramid is one option you have for how to structure a storyline.

231
00:12:13,040 --> 00:12:15,880
You start with an exposition, which is basically the introduction.

232
00:12:16,120 --> 00:12:20,480
You have some sort of rising action, then a climactic moment, the point of no return.

233
00:12:20,720 --> 00:12:21,880
Then you have falling action.

234
00:12:22,040 --> 00:12:22,960
And then the denouement.

235
00:12:22,960 --> 00:12:25,120
At the end, which is basically French for the ending.

236
00:12:25,160 --> 00:12:28,040
Now, Freitag's Pyramid is the structure of a tragedy.

237
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:33,400
So it might be that your climax comes 90% of the way through the story rather than right in the middle of the story.

238
00:12:33,440 --> 00:12:36,080
So you can obviously change this pyramid as necessary.

239
00:12:36,120 --> 00:12:38,640
Another good structure to look at is the seven point plot structure.

240
00:12:38,680 --> 00:12:42,200
For that, you start with a hook and then you move through a series of plot turns and pinches.

241
00:12:42,240 --> 00:12:49,160
Remember, pitch points are outside events that force your character to take action, while plot events are things that your character does to move the story forward.

242
00:12:49,200 --> 00:12:52,400
And I like the way that this one escalates all the way up to plot turn two.

243
00:12:52,440 --> 00:12:52,920
Climax.

244
00:12:52,960 --> 00:12:54,000
And then resolution.

245
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:58,480
But I will say that a lot of very famous short stories don't follow neat structures like this.

246
00:12:58,520 --> 00:13:00,360
Think of John Updike's A&P.

247
00:13:00,400 --> 00:13:05,560
It's about a boy working in a convenience store and he watches these girls come in who are extremely beautiful.

248
00:13:05,600 --> 00:13:08,880
And there's not exactly rising arc and climax.

249
00:13:08,920 --> 00:13:11,480
And I don't know, it's a different type of storyline.

250
00:13:11,520 --> 00:13:14,760
It's more of like a snapshot moment than a traditional arc.

251
00:13:14,800 --> 00:13:17,520
So I would consider using one of these narrative structures for your story.

252
00:13:17,560 --> 00:13:19,720
But don't feel like you absolutely have to.

253
00:13:19,760 --> 00:13:22,920
You always have a lot of latitude to change them as necessary to fit the topic.

254
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:25,440
And I think that's the type of story that you're trying to tell.

255
00:13:25,480 --> 00:13:36,400
But I will say that with my chess story, it does follow the general rising action to a climax of a cheater exposed at a chess tournament and what happens to that character and then the ending.

256
00:13:36,440 --> 00:13:42,120
So a lot of times you do end up following that because it's a great structure to get emotions out of the reader.

257
00:13:42,160 --> 00:13:43,680
And here is the very final step.

258
00:13:43,720 --> 00:13:45,320
And it's honestly my favorite one.

259
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:46,120
Experiment.

260
00:13:46,160 --> 00:13:48,720
In other words, try something crazy.

261
00:13:48,760 --> 00:13:51,760
What I like about this is the previous eight steps were pretty definite.

262
00:13:51,800 --> 00:13:52,720
Hey, do this.

263
00:13:52,720 --> 00:13:56,120
I mean, there's room to be creative, but in general it was very prescriptive.

264
00:13:56,160 --> 00:14:01,960
Well, experiment basically says, hey, throw out everything I just told you and try something different.

265
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:06,800
So let me give you some examples of how I've seen experiments go really well in short stories.

266
00:14:06,840 --> 00:14:08,680
One, try a hermit crab fiction.

267
00:14:08,720 --> 00:14:13,760
These are stories that slip into the shape of another form of writing, like a hermit crab moving to a new shell.

268
00:14:13,800 --> 00:14:22,400
You can write a story like a recipe or board game rules or a crossword puzzle or a Craigslist post or a PowerPoint presentation.

269
00:14:22,720 --> 00:14:25,560
For example, I can actually do this in a visit to the Goon Squad.

270
00:14:25,600 --> 00:14:30,680
You can write it as instructions or advice from a parent like Jamaica Kincaid does this in girl.

271
00:14:30,720 --> 00:14:33,480
A second option other than hermit crabs is metafiction.

272
00:14:33,520 --> 00:14:40,680
Break the fourth wall and talk directly to the reader or give a character your exact name or point out the implausibility of a coincidence in your story.

273
00:14:40,720 --> 00:14:41,680
A third option.

274
00:14:41,720 --> 00:14:43,280
Make your narrator unreliable.

275
00:14:43,320 --> 00:14:44,480
How are they going to lie?

276
00:14:44,520 --> 00:14:45,880
How are they going to slant the truth?

277
00:14:45,920 --> 00:14:51,240
To what extent are they unreliable, like wildly unreliable or just fibbing little here and there?

278
00:14:51,280 --> 00:14:52,480
A fourth way you can experiment.

279
00:14:52,480 --> 00:15:03,480
Try writing within specific restraints, like don't use any words that are longer than two syllables or pick two objects like a splinter and a dinner bell and then somehow find a way to include those in the story.

280
00:15:03,520 --> 00:15:16,480
Now, I have to say, for my story, I didn't experiment in any formal or technical way, but I still think this is a great step in the short story writing process because it opens up your mind to all sorts of possibilities for what you can do with a short story.

281
00:15:16,520 --> 00:15:20,120
I cannot wait to see all the short stories that you guys create based on this advice.

282
00:15:20,160 --> 00:15:22,240
Good luck writing and don't forget to subscribe and like.
